# MAGIC %md
# MAGIC ## 5. "So — was Databricks Asset Bundles (DABs) the answer?"  🎯
# MAGIC ### The honest version (say this out loud — it builds trust)
# MAGIC
# MAGIC **DABs by itself does *not* flatten the DAG.** If you wrap today's exploding job in a
# MAGIC bundle, you get the same exploding graph, just defined in YAML. That's the important
# MAGIC nuance.
# MAGIC
# MAGIC **What actually solves the scalability problem is the orchestration *pattern*:**
# MAGIC config-driven dispatch + a single parameterized notebook per stage + `for_each` fan-out.
# MAGIC Those work with or without DABs.
# MAGIC
# MAGIC **So why DABs is still the right call for you right now** — it's the vehicle that makes
# MAGIC that pattern maintainable and promotable:
# MAGIC
# MAGIC | DABs gives you | Why it matters to this team |
# MAGIC |---|---|
# MAGIC | **Define once, deploy to dev/test/prod** by changing variables (catalog/schema) | Promote the same engine across environments with no code changes |
# MAGIC | **Everything as version-controlled code** (jobs + notebooks + config) | Reproducible, reviewable, roll-back-able — matters for evaluations that drive contract decisions |
# MAGIC | **Parameterization** wired from YAML → notebook widgets | This is the "the YAML feeds the pipeline" idea — it's what enables the dispatcher pattern cleanly |
# MAGIC | **Resource globbing** (`resources/*.yml`) | Drop in a new job file and it's part of the bundle |
# MAGIC
# MAGIC **The accurate soundbite:** *"DABs is how we package and ship it across environments;
# MAGIC config + `for_each` is what keeps the orchestration flat. The demo uses both together —
# MAGIC that combination is the answer."*
# MAGIC
# MAGIC ⚠️ **Don't say** "DABs solves the branching problem." It doesn't on its own, and a sharp
# MAGIC engineer on their team will catch it.

